An Open Letter To Monitoring/Metrics/Alerting Companies


01. May
/
Cognitive Systems Engineering, Tools, WebOps /
15 Comments








Iâ€™d like to open up a dialogue with companies who are selling X-As-A-Service products that are focused on assisting operations and development teams in tracking the health and performance of their software systems.

Note: Itâ€™s likely my suggestions below are understood and embraced by many companies already. I know a number of them who are paying attention to all areas I would want them to, and/or make sure theyâ€™re not making claims about their product that arenâ€™t genuine.Â 

Anomaly detection is important. It canâ€™t be overlooked. We as a discipline need to pay attention to it, and continually get better at it.
But for the companies who rely on your value-add selling point(s) as:

â€œour product will tell you when things are going wrongâ€ and/or
â€œour product will automatically fix things when it finds something is wrongâ€

the implication is these things will somehow relieve the engineer from thinking or doing anything about those activities, so they can focus on more â€˜importantâ€™ things. â€œWell-designed automation will keep people from having to do tedious workâ€, the cartoon-like salesman says.
Please stop doing this. Itâ€™s a lie in the form of marketing material and itâ€™s a huge boondoggle that distracts us away from focusing on what we should work on, which is to augment and assistÂ people in solving problems.

Anomaly detection in software is, and always will be, anÂ unsolved problem.Â Your company will not solve it. Your software will not solve it. Our people will improvise around it and adapt their work to cope with the fact that we will not always know what and how something is wrong at the exact time we need to know.

My suggestion is to first acknowledge this (that your attempts to detect anomalies perfectly, at the right time, is not possible) when you talk to potential customers. Want my business? Say this up front, so we can then move on to talking about how your software willÂ assistÂ my team of expert humans who willÂ alwaysÂ be smarter than your code.
In other words, your monitoring software should take theÂ Tony Stark approach, not theÂ WOPR/HAL9000Â approach.
These are things Iâ€™d like to know about how you thought about your product:

Tell me about how you usedÂ qualitative researchÂ in developing your product.
Tell me about how you observed actual engineers in their natural habitat, in the real world, as they detected and responded to anomalies that arose.
Show me your findings from when you had actual UX/UI professionals consider carefully how the interfaces of your product should be designed.
Demonstrate toÂ me the people designing your product haveÂ actually been on-callÂ and have experience with the scenario where they needed to understand what the hell was going on, had no idea where to startÂ looking, all under time and consequence pressure.
Show me the people who are building your product take as a first design principle that outages and other â€œuntowardâ€ events are handled not by a lone engineer, but moreÂ often then notÂ by aÂ teamÂ of engineers all with their different expertise and focus of attention.Â Successful response depends on not just on anomalyÂ detection,Â but how the team shares the observations they are making amongst each other in order to come up with actions to take.

Â 
Stop thinking youâ€™re trying to solve aÂ troubleshootingÂ problem; youâ€™re not.
Â 
The world youâ€™re trying to sell to is in the business ofÂ dynamic fault management.Â This means that quite often you canâ€™t just take a component out of serviceÂ and investigate whatâ€™s wrong with it. It means diagnosis involves testing hypotheses that could actually make things a lot worse than they already are. This means that phases of responding to issues have overlappingÂ concerns all at the same time. Things like:

I donâ€™t know what is going on.
I have a guess about what is going on, but Iâ€™m not sure, and I donâ€™t know how to confirm it.
Because of what Sue and Alice said, and what I see, I think what is going on is X.
Since we think X is happening, I think we should do Y.
Is there a chance that Y will make things worse?
If we donâ€™t know whatâ€™s happening with N, can we do M so things donâ€™t get worse, or we can buy time to figure out what to do about N?
Do we think this thing (that we have no clue about) is changing for the better or the worse?
etc.

Instead of telling me about how your software will solve problems, show me youâ€™re trying to build a product that is going to join my team as an awesome team member, because Iâ€™m going to think about using/buying your service in the same way I think about hiring.
Sincerely,
John Allspaw
